38
00:01:37,519 --> 00:01:39,599
but there are dials on loads of things.

39
00:01:39,599 --> 00:01:41,280
They aren't just on clocks.

40
00:01:41,280 --> 00:01:43,680
And a bell is, well, a bell.

41
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:48,719
Well, hurry up, Neil.

42
00:01:48,719 --> 00:01:51,200
You're wasting time with all these explanations.

43
00:01:51,200 --> 00:01:52,799
That's cheeky coming from you, Rob.

44
00:01:52,799 --> 00:01:55,120
I think the answer is probably bell.

45
00:01:55,120 --> 00:01:59,600
Well, you could be right, because not all timepieces go tick tock.

46
00:01:59,600 --> 00:02:05,040
In fact, mechanical clocks and watches are quite recent in the history of timekeeping.

47
00:02:05,040 --> 00:02:07,840
Mechanical means to do with machines.

48
00:02:07,840 --> 00:02:11,280
So in the past, before people had mechanical timepieces,

49
00:02:11,280 --> 00:02:15,439
how did they know when to arrive at work, for example, or when to finish?

50
00:02:15,439 --> 00:02:19,200
They would have looked up at the sky and observed how the position of the sun,

51
00:02:19,200 --> 00:02:22,159
the moon and the stars changed as time passed.

52
00:02:22,159 --> 00:02:23,840
That doesn't sound very precise.

53
00:02:23,920 --> 00:02:24,560
Precisely.

54
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:26,719
It means accurate or exact.

55
00:02:26,719 --> 00:02:29,360
It was precise enough for many people.

56
00:02:29,360 --> 00:02:33,840
Let's listen to the director of the museum of the history of science in Oxford,

57
00:02:33,840 --> 00:02:36,480
Dr. Silke Ackerman, talking about this.

58
00:02:38,240 --> 00:02:45,520
We certainly gain precision, but we completely get devolved or divorced from where time

59
00:02:45,520 --> 00:02:46,960
originally came from.

60
00:02:46,960 --> 00:02:50,159
The time we use was based on the movement of the sun.

61
00:02:51,120 --> 00:02:58,879
And it's roughly still in sync, but for many societies, it wasn't at all relevant to know

62
00:02:58,879 --> 00:03:00,240
that it's four o'clock.

63
00:03:00,240 --> 00:03:06,960
They needed to know how much daylight have I got left or when is the prayer time I need to observe

64
00:03:07,680 --> 00:03:09,759
for completely different reasons.

65
00:03:09,759 --> 00:03:14,879
And whilst precision is wonderful, it's also very much a straight jacket.

66
00:03:14,879 --> 00:03:21,039
Everybody is dominated by looking at the watch or smartphone all the time when you observe people.

67
00:03:21,039 --> 00:03:23,120
So we've basically become a slave to time.

68
00:03:25,039 --> 00:03:29,280
So in the past, they had different reasons for wanting to know the time, is that it?

69
00:03:29,280 --> 00:03:34,719
Yes. In ancient times, people were concerned about the changing of the seasons and how this affected them.

70
00:03:34,719 --> 00:03:39,359
When it was time to plant crops or when to harvest them, when the rainy season was going to start.

71
00:03:39,359 --> 00:03:44,479
Now you mention it in the Muslim world, the start of Ramadan is traditionally calculated

72
00:03:44,479 --> 00:03:47,759
by the rising of the present moon, which changes every year.

73
00:03:48,239 --> 00:03:51,840
And you can't calculate that with modern methods of timekeeping.

74
00:03:51,840 --> 00:03:53,439
You're catching on Neil.

75
00:03:53,439 --> 00:03:57,439
Now what does Dr. Akhamam mean when she says precision is a straight jacket?

76
00:03:57,439 --> 00:04:03,359
She means that always wanting to be precise about time can limit what we do in a way that is damaging.

77
00:04:03,839 --> 00:04:06,399
So we need to take our time, relax a bit.

78
00:04:06,399 --> 00:04:08,319
That's my philosophy for life.

79
00:04:08,319 --> 00:04:10,719
But we are seriously running out of time now Rob.

80
00:04:10,719 --> 00:04:13,759
